{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513277"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12077"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12077"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.23,0.03,0.18,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4631"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78419"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4631"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63781"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78419"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the emergency department after he accidentally spilled hydrochloric acid on his right hand 10 minutes ago. He felt immediate pain, washed his hand in some water and then presented for further management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is a wound on the lateral aspect of the dorsum of his right hand extending proximally to the wrist on top of the ulnar styloid prominence. The fingers are spared. The skin is red and blotchy with signs of black skin on the edges. Capillary refill time is 5 seconds with diminished sensation to pain and touch.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Irrigation of the wound with cool running water for 20 minutes","Perform immediate wound debridement and excise non-viable tissues","Test the pH of the wound","Administer neutralising agent to the wound","Administer prophylactic antibiotic"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChemical burns are a common injury that require prompt treatment, and referral to a specialist burns unit. It is important for clinicians to be familiar with initial assessment and treatment of chemical burns as research has shown that proper first-aid leads to faster recovery rate and reduced hospital stay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial assessment of chemical burn should include rapid history on the type of chemical agent, the state of chemical (liquid/solid), quantity, duration of contact, extent of penetration, and the type of emergency management that the patient received. It is also important to consider systemic effects of several chemical agents. For example, hydrofluoric acid may lead to severe cardiac arrhythmia due to hypocalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmergency treatment of chemical burn is similar to thermal burn in which exposure and removal of the causative agent should be done first. This include removing affected clothing or accessories. Next,\u003Cstrong\u003E the wound should be properly irrigated with running water for 20 minutes. \u003C/strong\u003EIrrigation allows removal of causative agent and decreased duration of contact which leads to decreased severity of the wound. However, it is important to remember that irrigation should not be done in patients whose burn injury is due to metallic agents (lithium, phosphate etc). This could start a chemical reaction which may worsen the burn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBurns cooled for 20 minutes show greater re-epithelisation than other time periods. Any clothing that is adherent to the underlying skin should be left untouched and immediately the wounds cooled for 20 minutes with continuous running water (if possible) in partial thickness and superficial burns, but not full thickness burns. Patients with a large burn (TBSA \u0026gt; 10%) or children/older people should be observed for hypothermia and in such circumstances cooling should be ceased. In circumstances where running water is not available, wet towels or saline soaked gauze should be applied to the affected areas. These should be changed frequently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWound debridement and excising non-viable tissues\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of burns management. Removing dead skin non-viable tissue will decrease the likelihood of wound infection. However, proper irrigation of the wound should be done first, especially in patients who present as acutely as this case - within 15 minutes of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesting the pH of the wound and administering neutralising agent to the wound \u003C/strong\u003Eis not routinely done as part of first-aid management of chemical burns. Applying neutralising agent to the wound without proper caution may lead to further injury. Irrigation with warm water has shown to be the most beneficial immediate treatment, with lower error rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProphylactic IV antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Eare not routinely indicated, except in the case of severely contaminated burns, after discussion with a tertiary burns service.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wound caused by chemical burn should be irrigated with cool water for 20 minutes to decrease the severity of burn.","The routine use of IV antibiotics in burns patients is not routinely indicated"],"references":["Gnaneswaran N, Perera E, Perera M, Sawhney R. Cutaneous chemical burns: assessment and early management. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Mar;44(3):135-9. PMID: 25770579. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25770579/","Ngan, V. Chemical Burn. DermNet web page. 2007. Accessed on September 2022. Available via: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/chemical-burn","Walsh K, Hughes I, Dheansa B. Management of chemical burns. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2022 Mar 2;83(3):1-12. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2020.0056. Epub 2022 Mar 4. PMID: 35377199. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35377199/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63781"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12077"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63781"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T18:18:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T18:20:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4631"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78419"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":nul